		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 class="first"><a href="#p126284">Re: DIY Yogurt</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/post126284.html?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d#p126284"><img src="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/styles/art_elegance_taiwanease/imageset/icon_topic_latest.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/member/Dragonbones/?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d" style="color: #000066;" class="username-coloured">Dragonbones</a></strong> &raquo; Tue May 31, 2016 16:41 </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>SlowRain wrote:</cite>are there any issues that are relevant to yogurt-making in Taiwan, particularly regarding ingredients (milk) or climate?</div></blockquote><br /><br />I just use whole or 2% milk, heat it in the evening on the stovetop or microwave (to about 113 F or 44C, checked with an instant-read thermometer I use for bread baking, or ‘very warm but not hot’ to the touch), add a Tbsp or so of live culture yogurt (room temperature is ideal; any brand of unsweetened that says 活菌; UniPres. AB is fine), stir, cover, leave it undisturbed (don’t tilt or shake or stir it at all) and check it the next morning. <br /><br />In the winter I will leave the thermometer in it so I can monitor the temp., and put it somewhere warm, e.g. in a water bath that I can add hot water to now and then, or perhaps turning on a hot pad near it occasionally to try to keep it roughly in the 35-45 degree range. I cover it with some towels too, but I really haven’t had to be too fussy about it, especially not in summers above 33C. The bacteria involved work through a pretty wide range of temps IME; they just take longer as it gets cooler, but I get smooth creamy yogurt by starting it at the top of the temp range, allowing the temp to fall slowly, bringing it back up perhaps once, then letting it fall again slowly overnight.  Occasionally in winter I have to warm it back up again in the morning and leave it another 4-6 hours (rare).</div>

			<div id="sig126284" class="signature">“To cook for the pleasure of it, to devote a portion of our leisure to it, is to declare our independence from the corporations seeking to organize our every waking moment into yet another occasion for consumption.&quot; --Michael Pollan</div>
                        <hr />
                        
