		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p126292">Re: DIY Yogurt</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/post126292.html?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d#p126292"><img src="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/styles/art_elegance_taiwanease/imageset/icon_topic_latest.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/member/Toad/?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d">Toad</a></strong> &raquo; Tue May 31, 2016 21:55 </p>

			

			<div class="content">I used to heat it quite high and then let it cool; I think it was dragonbones' suggestion to just warm it, on the basis that the milk is already pasteurized anyway. This is what I now do - it's a lot simpler!  I have frozen cubes of yoghurt starter, so if I heat the milk to about 55'C and drop the cube in, it's ready to go. If the weather is warm I just stick it it a ceramic pot and leave it. Otherwise, I hold it at 45-50'C in a toaster oven. The temperature profile <span style="font-weight: bold">does </span>make a big difference to the taste and texture.</div>

			
                        <hr />
                        
                        <div class="content">
                                
