		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p126334">Re: DIY Yogurt</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/post126334.html?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d#p126334"><img src="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/styles/art_elegance_taiwanease/imageset/icon_topic_latest.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/member/cranky%20laowai/?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d" style="color: #000066;" class="username-coloured">cranky laowai</a></strong> &raquo; Thu Jun 02, 2016 10:30 </p>

			

			<div class="content">My answers below are based on my own experience, not on any special knowledge. Experiment and see what works best for you. <br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div>My goal is a slightly thick texture, maybe like a pudding or something similar to that.  I'm not going to be drinking it or cooking with it.  About how many hours should I let it sit?</div></blockquote>  <br />I'd say 10-12 hours. Probably longer if you don't have anything to keep the yogurt warm (And if you don't, at least wrap the container in some towels to insulate it.) Maybe longer still in the winter if without a heater.<br /><br />If you want <span style="font-style: italic">really</span> thick stuff (i.e., Greek yogurt), you'll need to strain it with cheesecloth. But that's too much trouble for me. <br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div>Does the sitting affect the texture or the taste, or both? </div></blockquote> <br />Probably both. Definitely the texture. <br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div>Am I correct in assuming my initial choice for what I use as a starter will have the biggest impact on taste?</div></blockquote><br />That can make a big difference, yes. The milk, too. <br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>SlowRain wrote:</cite>What about flavoring?  What do you do, even if it may seem a little strange?</div></blockquote><br />Sorry, I have no especially colorful suggestions. I tend to go with one or more of the following: <br /><ul><li>whatever jam happens to be in the fridge</li><li>cinnamon</li><li>raisins</li><li>honey</li><li>lemon curd</li><li>bananas</li><li>my wife likes to add chia seeds (but let them absorb some of the yogurt before eating)</li></ul></div>

			<div id="sig126334" class="signature"><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.pinyin.info/news/">http://www.pinyin.info/news/</a><!-- m --></div>
