	<div id="p126336" class="post bg2">
		<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p126336">Re: DIY Yogurt</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/post126336.html?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d#p126336"><img src="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/styles/art_elegance_taiwanease/imageset/icon_topic_latest.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/member/Toad/?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d">Toad</a></strong> &raquo; Thu Jun 02, 2016 11:00 </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>SlowRain wrote:</cite>Thanks for the replies.<br /><br />My goal is a slightly thick texture, maybe like a pudding or something similar to that.  I'm not going to be drinking it or cooking with it.  About how many hours should I let it sit?  Does the sitting affect the texture or the taste, or both?  Am I correct in assuming my initial choice for what I use as a starter will have the biggest impact on taste?<br /><br />What about flavoring?  What do you do, even if it may seem a little strange?</div></blockquote><br /><br />Sitting time mostly affects flavour: longer will make it more sour. Temperature will also affect flavour because yoghurt cultures contain several different bacteria, with slightly different temperature preferences, but it primarily affects coagulation. Warmer will give you a separated whey and a yoghurt with a distinct graininess (as opposed to smooth, homogeneous curds).<br /><br />I always strain my yoghurt (I don't much like the tart flavour, which comes mostly from the whey). If you fermented at a lower temperature for a relatively short time, you'll get an amazing Greek-style product by straining - just add honey and nuts!  If you ferment warmer and longer, and then strain, you'll end up with something more like labneh, which goes well with diced cucumber and mint, or olives. If you strain it overnight, you'll get 'yoghurt cheese', which can be used much like cream cheese.<br /><br />I use a dofu cloth (easily available in the everything shops) for straining.</div>

			
                        <hr />
                        
