		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p126636">Re: DIY Yogurt</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/post126636.html?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d#p126636"><img src="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/styles/art_elegance_taiwanease/imageset/icon_topic_latest.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/member/Toad/?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d">Toad</a></strong> &raquo; Wed Jun 08, 2016 13:18 </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>SlowRain wrote:</cite>Can I strain the yogurt through a sterilized tea strainer, or is the tofu cloth better? </div></blockquote><br />It won't be fine enough. You can probably use a piece of clean cotton clothing.<br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div>I may consider a cup of that AB as my starter, but are there any stores that have a variety of cultures to choose from and are specifically targeting people making yogurt at home? </div></blockquote><br />I use that one. I just prefer the flavour. Make sure to get the no-sugar one.<br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div>What about the simple counter-top method which, as I understand it, doesn't require any heating, and where time, more so than temperature, is the important factor?</div></blockquote><br />Works fine as long as the weather is hot. Like, July-August hot, but you might get away with it.  You will still need to microwave the milk up to about 45'C to get it started, but after that it'll sort of run along under its own steam.</div>

			
                        <hr />
                        
