	<div id="p126896" class="post bg1">
		<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p126896">Re: DIY Yogurt</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/post126896.html?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d#p126896"><img src="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/styles/art_elegance_taiwanease/imageset/icon_topic_latest.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/member/SlowRain/?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d">SlowRain</a></strong> &raquo; Tue Jun 14, 2016 08:10 </p>

			

			<div class="content">Well, I've had some success.  The first time, I didn't use a yogurt with live active cultures.  The second time, I bought an unsweetened eating yogurt made by Fresh Delight.  I scalded my milk at about 85°C, and I incubated for 10 hours in my Tatung at about 45°C for most of the time (it fluctuated between 44-46°).  It turned out a little thicker, grainier, and more sour than the original.  Next time, I'll incubate shorter.  The test will be to see how long I can keep making yogurt from this one culture.<br /><br />On a side note, the Tatung does a not bad job for maintaining the temperature of a water bath.  I preheated it with one cup of water, and then I just left it plugged in and used the automatic warming feature that it has.  I had to leave the lid ever so slightly uncovered.  The main drawback is that it's so short you can only use small jam jars and not the large one-quart pasta sauce ones.  Still, it seems to be my best option for now.<br /><br /><img src="https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Ck3lIBRUUAAdqAc.jpg:small" alt="Image" /></div>

			
                        <hr />
                        
                        <div class="content">
                                
                                <dl class="postbody small">
