		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p126906">Re: DIY Yogurt</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/post126906.html?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d#p126906"><img src="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/styles/art_elegance_taiwanease/imageset/icon_topic_latest.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="https://taiwanease.com/en/forums/member/Toad/?sid=cb0962ece7560f5c49d802b3bbe6ae1d">Toad</a></strong> &raquo; Tue Jun 14, 2016 11:03 </p>

			

			<div class="content">I'd wondered if a rice cooker might do the job but never felt inclined to risk a litre of milk on it.  Nice to know it really works!<br /><br />I imagine you could just put the milk in some suitably-sized crockpot and stick that in the ricecooker. There's no need to have a actual air seal as long as it's more-or-less anaerobic. However if you do it the way you did it, I guess you're more likely to end up with a pure culture that you can use over and over.</div>

			

		</div>

		


